FOREMAN: So's his EKG.
It's not his heart.

50
00:03:54,367 --> 00:03:55,891
We're being too nice.

51
00:03:56,836 --> 00:03:58,701
Outside the hospital
he can't breathe.

52
00:03:58,771 --> 00:04:01,171
Inside the hospital he can,
because we help,

53
00:04:01,241 --> 00:04:03,471
at least enough
to screw with
our test results.

54
00:04:03,543 --> 00:04:06,205
The source of
the problem's either
in his heart or his lungs,

55
00:04:06,646 --> 00:04:08,876
so all we gotta do is
stop helping,

56
00:04:08,948 --> 00:04:11,314
put a little pressure on him
and see which gives out first.

57
00:04:11,384 --> 00:04:15,548
At 71, we get his heart
or lungs to give out, we might
not get them to give in again.

58
00:04:15,622 --> 00:04:17,590
That's why we're gonna do it
in a hospital.

59
00:04:17,657 --> 00:04:20,956
Put him on an
inclined treadmill
and do a stress EKG.

60
00:04:22,895 --> 00:04:24,419
So much for the admiration.

61
00:04:25,598 --> 00:04:29,659
Let's get you started.
I'll turn your oxygen up.

62
00:04:32,305 --> 00:04:33,294
I...

63
00:04:33,473 --> 00:04:37,739
I worked with Williams
on the first protocol
for this machine.

64
00:04:37,810 --> 00:04:39,641
Everyone still uses it.

65
00:04:39,746 --> 00:04:43,409
Except for Williams.
He died four years ago.

66
00:04:43,483 --> 00:04:44,882
I'm sorry.

67
00:04:45,318 --> 00:04:48,116
He was 84.
He died parasailing.

68
00:04:49,756 --> 00:04:52,020
He was always an idiot.

69
00:04:54,127 --> 00:04:55,389
You okay?

70
00:04:55,895 --> 00:04:59,524
Hang in there.
You know the protocol's
only a few minutes.

71
00:05:00,633 --> 00:05:02,157
FOREMAN:
His heart rate's flat.

72
00:05:02,235 --> 00:05:04,430
If we don't get it past 130,
we're not going to
see anything.

73
00:05:04,504 --> 00:05:06,972
And if he falls
and breaks a hip, we're not
going to see anything either.

74
00:05:07,040 --> 00:05:10,134
Except an increase
in our malpractice insurance.

75
00:05:12,045 --> 00:05:14,536
I figured House might
go back to the pills,

76
00:05:14,614 --> 00:05:17,811
but if he's using his cane,
he's right back
to where he was before.

77
00:05:17,884 --> 00:05:18,976
Maybe even worse.

78
00:05:19,052 --> 00:05:22,146
Luckily, he'll handle it
in a stoic, grown-up fashion.

79
00:05:22,221 --> 00:05:24,416
He'd never take it out on us.

80
00:05:29,128 --> 00:05:30,356
I can't.

81
00:05:30,663 --> 00:05:32,688
I've got to stop.

82
00:05:33,166 --> 00:05:34,997
Just a little longer.

83
00:05:39,539 --> 00:05:43,270
His heart rate's only 90.
I'm going to increase
the incline.

84
00:05:45,712 --> 00:05:48,203
I've got to stop.
I've got to get off.

85
00:05:48,381 --> 00:05:50,246
You're doing great.
Just a little faster, okay?

86
00:05:50,316 --> 00:05:53,877
I don't need a cheerleader,
I need oxygen.

87
00:05:55,188 --> 00:05:57,179
Stop. This isn't working.

88
00:06:02,762 --> 00:06:04,730
His heart rate
barely got above 90.

89
00:06:04,797 --> 00:06:07,288
He can't breathe.
There's too much fluid
in his lungs.

90
00:06:07,367 --> 00:06:09,858
Really?
He's got fluid in his lungs?

91
00:06:09,936 --> 00:06:12,700
Whatever are we gonna do?
Oh, yeah, now I remember.

92
00:06:12,772 --> 00:06:15,400
Put him on a treadmill
and run him like
one of his rats on a wheel.

93
00:06:15,475 --> 00:06:16,874
He can't run.
He can hardly walk.

94
00:06:16,943 --> 00:06:18,308
That's 'cause he's not
trying hard enough.

95
00:06:18,378 --> 00:06:19,811
If he was, his heart rate
would go up.

96
00:06:19,879 --> 00:06:22,677
Exercising with a lung full of
your own bodily fluids
tends to hurt.

97
00:06:22,749 --> 00:06:25,445
They don't call it
a stress test for nothing.
Do it again.

98
00:06:25,518 --> 00:06:26,507
He's drowning.

99
00:06:26,586 --> 00:06:30,249
Then pull him out of the pool
and do it again.

100
00:06:34,227 --> 00:06:38,527
I'm assuming this isn't
your idea of
a long-term solution.

101
00:06:38,631 --> 00:06:40,223
We need to get rid
of the fluid in your lungs,

102
00:06:40,299 --> 00:06:41,698
so you'll be able to
do the test.

103
00:06:41,768 --> 00:06:44,032
To see if it's my heart
or my lungs?

104
00:06:44,103 --> 00:06:45,263
Exactly.

105
00:06:45,338 --> 00:06:46,600
My money's on both.

106
00:06:47,774 --> 00:06:50,868
I've been in and out
of the hospital
for the past year.

107
00:06:50,943 --> 00:06:55,107
I'm old. I'm sick.
And I'm getting older
and sicker.

108
00:06:55,348 --> 00:06:58,715
Not a very interesting
differential but...

109
00:07:00,319 --> 00:07:01,547
I'm in.

110
00:07:10,830 --> 00:07:13,526
You don't need a $400 handbag.

111
00:07:13,599 --> 00:07:16,591
It's kinda hard to check
your throat when you're
flapping your gums around.

112
00:07:16,702 --> 00:07:17,794
Sorry.

113
00:07:17,870 --> 00:07:19,428
But it's for the fall formal.

114
00:07:20,206 --> 00:07:22,902
He doesn't care if it's
for the Presidential
Inauguration.

115
00:07:22,975 --> 00:07:25,910
But I'm using Marissa'a
old dress. It's free.

116
00:07:25,978 --> 00:07:27,570
You know what else is free?

117
00:07:27,647 --> 00:07:31,014
The roof over your head,
the food you eat,
your phone, your computer.

118
00:07:31,083 --> 00:07:32,209
How long have you
been congested?

119
00:07:32,285 --> 00:07:34,685
All week, ever since we
got back from Fresno.

120
00:07:34,754 --> 00:07:38,019
Fresno? That's in France,
right? See the Parthenon?

121
00:07:38,724 --> 00:07:40,089
California.

122
00:07:40,493 --> 00:07:43,257
I've got no appetite,
I'm aching all over, I'm weak.

123
00:07:43,362 --> 00:07:45,557
Does that hurt?
Oh, yeah.

124
00:07:46,098 --> 00:07:50,159
Does his voice always have
that unattractive nasal tone?

125
00:07:50,536 --> 00:07:51,764
Totally.

126
00:07:53,306 --> 00:07:55,831
I'm gonna take that giggle
as a "no".

127
00:07:55,908 --> 00:07:58,502
Fever, aches, weakness,
loss of appetite.

128
00:07:58,578 --> 00:08:01,308
You been having an anal sex
with IV drug users lately?

129
00:08:01,380 --> 00:08:03,473
Of course not. I'm married.

130
00:08:03,816 --> 00:08:05,147
You think she might have
been having...

131
00:08:05,218 --> 00:08:06,742
No!

132
00:08:07,286 --> 00:08:08,617
Probably a rhinovirus.

133
00:08:08,688 --> 00:08:09,814
What's that?

134
00:08:10,389 --> 00:08:11,583
A cold.

135
00:08:12,258 --> 00:08:15,785
Take this four times a day,
and stay off airplanes.

136
00:08:15,862 --> 00:08:17,887
They're flying cesspools.

137
00:08:19,665 --> 00:08:20,757
Oops!

138
00:08:21,901 --> 00:08:23,801
You dropped something.

139
00:08:24,704 --> 00:08:28,196
If there's anything else
you can think of, please call.

140
00:08:31,410 --> 00:08:32,434
Yes?

141
00:08:32,512 --> 00:08:34,139
He's too old and weak.

142
00:08:44,290 --> 00:08:47,282
Yeah, this is way better.
This'll work.

143
00:08:48,127 --> 00:08:49,424
Just try.

144
00:08:49,695 --> 00:08:53,187
There are 20 words
to describe chest pain.

145
00:08:53,266 --> 00:08:57,293
Burning, squeezing,
stabbing, tearing...

146
00:08:57,370 --> 00:08:59,702
Each one
diagnostically useful.

147
00:09:00,373 --> 00:09:03,240
For that,
you have to thank
Dr. Powell's textbook.

148
00:09:03,309 --> 00:09:07,211
But there are no words
to describe degrees of what
he's feeling right now.

149
00:09:07,280 --> 00:09:09,043
Shortness of breath.

150
00:09:09,849 --> 00:09:13,012
If he had worked
on those issues,
there would be.

151
00:09:13,286 --> 00:09:15,754
He never would have given up
until he had an answer.

152
00:09:15,821 --> 00:09:17,550
This isn't working.

153
00:09:20,927 --> 00:09:22,451
Dr. House...

154
00:09:22,528 --> 00:09:23,654
Please don't get up.

155
00:09:23,729 --> 00:09:25,424
I'm sure you're very busy,

156
00:09:25,498 --> 00:09:28,467
I'm just gonna try
and speed things up a little.

157
00:09:28,534 --> 00:09:30,331
Is that epi?
That's not the protocol.

158
00:09:30,403 --> 00:09:35,466
No. The protocol is
what you tried to do
and failed each time.

159
00:09:39,679 --> 00:09:41,806
Over 100. Now we're
getting somewhere.

160
00:09:41,881 --> 00:09:43,041
How does it look, Foreman?

161
00:09:43,115 --> 00:09:44,639
No EKG changes.

162
00:09:45,885 --> 00:09:46,943
Then we push harder.

163
00:09:47,019 --> 00:09:48,350
House, you're gonna kill him.

164
00:09:48,421 --> 00:09:51,015
No, he's right. Let him do it.

165
00:09:51,457 --> 00:09:53,789
See? That's why he doesn't
have to wear knee socks.

166
00:09:53,859 --> 00:09:55,486
He can't breathe.

167
00:09:59,398 --> 00:10:02,390
130, our magic number.

168
00:10:03,336 --> 00:10:05,395
Nothing here. Foreman?

169
00:10:05,471 --> 00:10:06,768
Still no sign of blockage.

170
00:10:08,641 --> 00:10:12,008
Which means
it's not the heart.
It must be the lungs.

171
00:10:13,112 --> 00:10:15,512
See, that wasn't so hard,
was it?

172
00:10:17,683 --> 00:10:20,208
No. Just give me the rest
of the epinephrine.

173
00:10:20,286 --> 00:10:22,516
The test is over. It's okay.
We're going to stabilize you.

174
00:10:22,588 --> 00:10:23,748
No.

175
00:10:24,323 --> 00:10:27,451
No, just let me die.

176
00:10:27,526 --> 00:10:28,515
You're not gonna die.

177
00:10:28,594 --> 00:10:30,391
Yes, I am.

178
00:10:30,463 --> 00:10:32,363
We'll find a treatment.

179
00:10:32,798 --> 00:10:35,733
I don't want to
live like this.

180
00:10:36,969 --> 00:10:40,427
Please, I'm begging you.

181
00:10:41,674 --> 00:10:42,902
Kill me.

182
00:10:48,481 --> 00:10:49,971
He says no more tests.

183
00:10:50,049 --> 00:10:52,279
He wants to die
and he wants us
to help him do it.

184
00:10:52,351 --> 00:10:55,718
And I wanna play
a little game I like to call
Block My Spike with Misty May.

185
00:10:55,788 --> 00:10:58,018
He's thought this through.
It's not
an impulsive decision.

186
00:10:58,090 --> 00:11:00,149
Neither is mine.
He's depressed.

187
00:11:00,226 --> 00:11:01,659
He'll feel much better
after we cure him.

188
00:11:01,727 --> 00:11:03,354
He's seen all the tests
we've seen.

189
00:11:03,429 --> 00:11:06,592
Even if we figure out what's
causing the lung damage,
it's too late to reverse it.

190
00:11:06,666 --> 00:11:08,566
You can't know that
without knowing what's wrong.

191
00:11:08,634 --> 00:11:09,999
It's his call.

192
00:11:10,069 --> 00:11:11,093
So what do we do?

193
00:11:11,170 --> 00:11:13,161
Do we just put a plastic bag
over his head
and get it over with?

194
00:11:13,239 --> 00:11:16,140
No, we give him
a syringe full of morphine.

195
00:11:18,210 --> 00:11:20,804
Every doctor
I've ever practiced with
has done it.

196
00:11:20,880 --> 00:11:22,541
They don't want to,
they don't like to,

197
00:11:22,615 --> 00:11:24,981
but that's the way it is.
I haven't. I won't.

198
00:11:25,051 --> 00:11:26,109
I couldn't do it either.

199
00:11:26,185 --> 00:11:28,244
You just said we should
respect his decision.

200
00:11:28,320 --> 00:11:30,720
Respect it doesn't necessarily
mean we honor it.

201
00:11:30,790 --> 00:11:33,384
Right. It just means
we talk about it.

202
00:11:33,693 --> 00:11:37,220
At some point, "do no harm"
has to mean allowing nature
to take its course,

203
00:11:37,296 --> 00:11:38,854
not stubbornly
standing in the way of it.

204
00:11:38,931 --> 00:11:42,298
Sticking a metal syringe
into a plastic IV line
and pumping in

205
00:11:42,368 --> 00:11:45,531
a lethal dose of morphine
is not letting nature
take its course,

206
00:11:45,604 --> 00:11:47,037
not according to
the State of New Jersey.

207
00:11:47,106 --> 00:11:49,836
So it's better we allow him
to slowly suffocate
in his own plasma?

208
00:11:49,909 --> 00:11:52,036
Whose side are you on,
Senator?

209
00:11:52,111 --> 00:11:55,205
First respect his wishes,
then invade Iraq,
then get the troops home.

210
00:11:55,281 --> 00:11:57,249
Make up your mind.
Wow.

211
00:11:57,883 --> 00:12:00,113
There's certainly
a lot of interesting things
to consider.

212
00:12:00,186 --> 00:12:02,620
The stress EKG
rules out the heart,

213
00:12:02,722 --> 00:12:04,417
which means something's
gotta be attacking his lungs.

214
00:12:04,490 --> 00:12:07,982
Could be mycoplasma
or Strep pneumo,
which probably means

215
00:12:08,060 --> 00:12:10,426
it's too late
to do anything about it.

216
00:12:10,496 --> 00:12:12,327
We could try levofloxacin.

217
00:12:12,398 --> 00:12:14,457
Coming up with a new treatment
isn't gonna do us any good

218
00:12:14,533 --> 00:12:16,797
unless we convince him
it's worth trying.

219
00:12:16,869 --> 00:12:20,828
Come on. He's old
and sick and tiny.

220
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:23,031
And we can do
whatever we want to him.

221
00:12:23,309 --> 00:12:25,709
(PAGERS BEEPING)

222
00:12:32,885 --> 00:12:34,477
What happened?

223
00:12:34,553 --> 00:12:35,850
I don't know.

224
00:12:35,921 --> 00:12:37,183
He must have fallen out of bed

225
00:12:37,256 --> 00:12:40,350
and got the nasal canula
wrapped around his neck
somehow.

226
00:12:40,426 --> 00:12:42,394
Ezra, what are you doing?

227
00:12:42,461 --> 00:12:47,091
I don't want to live
hooked to machines,
too weak to wipe my own ass.

228
00:12:47,166 --> 00:12:48,565
Why would you want to
wipe your own ass

229
00:12:48,634 --> 00:12:50,226
when you could have someone
do it for you?

230
00:12:50,302 --> 00:12:51,769
You're wasting your time.

231
00:12:51,837 --> 00:12:54,067
There must be other patients
you could actually help.

232
00:12:54,140 --> 00:12:58,133
All services rendered
on a first come,
first served basis.

233
00:12:58,277 --> 00:13:00,939
I won't consent
to any more tests.

234
00:13:01,914 --> 00:13:04,906
And if anyone tries to
so much as touch me,

235
00:13:05,751 --> 00:13:08,049
I'll press charges
for assault.

236
00:13:10,189 --> 00:13:11,486
You heard the man.

237
00:13:11,557 --> 00:13:15,357
He wants everyone to
leave him alone.
Why don't you go first?

238
00:13:16,629 --> 00:13:17,857
Get out!

239
00:13:27,106 --> 00:13:29,700
You came to me.
I didn't come to you.

240
00:13:30,109 --> 00:13:34,705
I figured you'd have the guts
to do what had to be done
if it came to that.

241
00:13:35,614 --> 00:13:39,050
We're nowhere near that.
It's time to test your lungs.

242
00:13:43,689 --> 00:13:44,951
Breathe!

243
00:13:45,024 --> 00:13:46,616
You're gonna have to
exhale sometime.

244
00:13:46,692 --> 00:13:47,681
Stop!

245
00:13:47,760 --> 00:13:49,091
House, you're hurting him.

246
00:13:49,161 --> 00:13:50,253
You're hurting me.

247
00:13:50,329 --> 00:13:52,160
(COUGHING)

248
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:58,561
Fine. If you don't help us,
we don't help you.

249
00:14:00,573 --> 00:14:03,371
Your lungs slowly
fill with fluid.

250
00:14:03,442 --> 00:14:06,570
You gasp to
catch every breath,
but never can.

251
00:14:06,645 --> 00:14:08,670
Every breath is petrifying.

252
00:14:09,582 --> 00:14:13,712
It'll be slow, painful,
torturous.

253
00:14:15,521 --> 00:14:19,719
We don't choose our birth.
And we don't choose our death.

254
00:14:22,094 --> 00:14:25,689
What if you could?
How about we make a deal?

255
00:14:26,699 --> 00:14:28,496
Give me one more day.

256
00:14:29,435 --> 00:14:33,064
If I don't find out exactly
what's wrong with you by then,

257
00:14:34,106 --> 00:14:36,233
I'll help you die.
House.

258
00:14:37,910 --> 00:14:39,571
Twenty-four hours.

259
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:43,280
Come on,
it's not gonna kill you.

260
00:14:51,090 --> 00:14:53,718
Old guy, lungs, fluid. Go.

261
00:14:53,792 --> 00:14:54,952
You cannot help him
kill himself.

262
00:14:55,027 --> 00:14:56,051
Of course I can.

263
00:14:56,128 --> 00:14:57,459
Chase says we do it
all the time.

264
00:14:57,529 --> 00:14:58,928
Cuddy is not gonna let you.

265
00:14:58,998 --> 00:15:00,260
Enough!

266
00:15:00,332 --> 00:15:01,959
You don't want me to kill him.
Fine.

267
00:15:02,034 --> 00:15:03,831
Here's a big shock.
I don't want to
kill him either.

268
00:15:03,903 --> 00:15:07,100
How do I not kill him?
By you guys doing your job.

269
00:15:07,373 --> 00:15:10,740
We have 24 hours to figure out
what's wrong with him.

270
00:15:11,010 --> 00:15:12,068
Tick-tock, tick-tock.

271
00:15:12,144 --> 00:15:14,908
I'll draw cultures. Pneumonia.
Should be bacteria
in his blood.

272
00:15:14,980 --> 00:15:16,470
That's gonna take
longer than 24 hours.

273
00:15:16,548 --> 00:15:17,776
Not if I spin down the sample.

274
00:15:17,850 --> 00:15:20,717
Separate off the buffy coat,
then Gram stain for bacteria.

275
00:15:20,886 --> 00:15:25,255
Great. Do an amylase, D-dimer,
C-reactive peptide,
get a urine,

276
00:15:25,324 --> 00:15:27,224
and do a bronchial sputum
while you're at it.

277
00:15:27,293 --> 00:15:29,887
And you, check his home
and lab for radiation
and toxins.

278
00:15:29,962 --> 00:15:31,259
And do a bone marrow biopsy.

279
00:15:31,330 --> 00:15:33,423
All of that in 24 hours?
Nah.

280
00:15:33,499 --> 00:15:37,196
Whatever you don't get done,
you can finish at the autopsy.

281
00:16:51,043 --> 00:16:53,978
Wow. You guys look like crap.

282
00:16:55,314 --> 00:16:56,406
What have you got?

283
00:16:56,482 --> 00:16:57,676
Purple dye on my fingers.

284
00:16:57,750 --> 00:16:59,081
What did the bone marrow
biopsy show?

285
00:16:59,151 --> 00:17:00,175
I don't have the results.

286
00:17:00,252 --> 00:17:02,243
What? What have you
been doing all night?

287
00:17:02,321 --> 00:17:04,152
Jell-O shots and wild sex,
what else?

288
00:17:04,223 --> 00:17:06,282
FOREMAN: There's no bacteria
in the blood cultures.

289
00:17:06,358 --> 00:17:08,519
We still have some cooking,
but so far, nothing.

290
00:17:08,594 --> 00:17:09,618
Nothing in the urine.

291
00:17:09,695 --> 00:17:13,096
Lab was clean enough
to do surgery in,
because, well, they do.

292
00:17:13,198 --> 00:17:14,529
And there was
no sign of viruses

293
00:17:14,600 --> 00:17:16,227
(CELL PHONE RINGING)
Or fleas on any of the rats.

294
00:17:16,368 --> 00:17:17,460
Yeah.

295
00:17:19,038 --> 00:17:20,096
Who?

296
00:17:21,040 --> 00:17:22,871
Tell her to call the clinic.

297
00:17:22,941 --> 00:17:26,172
Then tell her to
leave a message
and I'll get back to her.

298
00:17:26,245 --> 00:17:28,941
Then tell her to leave
a personal message.

299
00:17:29,014 --> 00:17:30,038
Who's that?

300
00:17:30,115 --> 00:17:31,412
That's your protégé.

301
00:17:31,483 --> 00:17:32,677
What are these?

302
00:17:32,751 --> 00:17:35,219
Dictation tapes.
He records everything.
Why?

303
00:17:35,287 --> 00:17:36,982
Because he's
a diligent researcher?

304
00:17:37,056 --> 00:17:38,546
Or he's losing his memory.

305
00:17:38,624 --> 00:17:39,955
A lot of people
dictate their notes.

306
00:17:40,025 --> 00:17:43,119
Yes, we could assume that
and we'd have nothing.

307
00:17:43,262 --> 00:17:44,388
Or we could assume
it's a symptom,

308
00:17:44,463 --> 00:17:47,728
in which case
whatever's in his lungs
is also in his brain,

309
00:17:47,800 --> 00:17:49,631
unless you've got
something more promising.

310
00:17:49,701 --> 00:17:51,191
I'll go get an MRI
of his head.

311
00:17:51,270 --> 00:17:53,238
Keep testing
till you find something.

312
00:17:53,305 --> 00:17:56,138
I'm going to my office
to rest for a while.

313
00:17:57,609 --> 00:18:01,739
It's been a long time
since I took an anatomy class,

314
00:18:01,814 --> 00:18:05,910
but I'm pretty sure you're
moving farther and farther
away from my lungs.

315
00:18:05,984 --> 00:18:08,475
Running out of places to look,
aren't you?

316
00:18:08,587 --> 00:18:10,646
It doesn't mean
we're gonna stop looking.

317
00:18:10,722 --> 00:18:12,986
Oh, no.
Not for six more hours.

318
00:18:13,092 --> 00:18:15,219
Do you want us to fail?
No.

319
00:18:16,061 --> 00:18:17,528
But you will.

320
00:18:26,939 --> 00:18:30,875
No abnormal nuclei means
no leukemia. He a drinker?

321
00:18:30,943 --> 00:18:32,308
Not according to the history.

322
00:18:32,377 --> 00:18:33,401
Which means yes, he drinks,

323
00:18:33,479 --> 00:18:36,346
which gives us a nice
mundane explanation
for the acellularity.

324
00:18:36,415 --> 00:18:39,475
Or he's telling the truth,
which means fungus
is still on the table.

325
00:18:39,551 --> 00:18:42,520
But your entire view
of human nature
gets destroyed.

326
00:18:42,588 --> 00:18:45,216
Six of one,
half a dozen of the other.

327
00:18:46,825 --> 00:18:49,350
Bad news fast. Good news,
you can take your time.

328
00:18:49,495 --> 00:18:51,963
Head's clean. You were wrong.
His faculties are intact.

329
00:18:52,030 --> 00:18:54,089
Too bad.
If his brain was addled,

330
00:18:54,166 --> 00:18:55,724
we wouldn't have
to listen to anything he says.

331
00:18:55,834 --> 00:18:57,426
Hand me the 10 percent KOH.

332
00:18:57,503 --> 00:18:59,198
It's 4:00.
We have nothing to tell him.

333
00:18:59,271 --> 00:19:02,206
Then we have no reason
to talk to him. We still
haven't ruled out fungus.

334
00:19:02,274 --> 00:19:04,902
Yeah, we have.
No bugs, no hyphae.

335
00:19:07,779 --> 00:19:10,680
Okay. Next procedure.

336
00:19:10,749 --> 00:19:13,240
We sneak in,
turn back the clock.

337
00:19:18,724 --> 00:19:22,751
Whole team. Must be bad news.

338
00:19:22,828 --> 00:19:23,954
Nope.

339
00:19:24,730 --> 00:19:27,927
Your bone marrow biopsy
revealed multiple myeloma.

340
00:19:28,367 --> 00:19:31,131
It's not good news,
but there are some treatments.

341
00:19:31,203 --> 00:19:32,363
I need to draw some blood.

342
00:19:32,437 --> 00:19:33,699
What about my breathing?

343
00:19:33,772 --> 00:19:38,141
Associated hyper-viscosity
syndrome gummed up the
blood vessels in your lungs.

344
00:19:38,210 --> 00:19:42,044
Dr. Chase said
my calcium is normal.

345
00:19:42,347 --> 00:19:44,440
We call him Dr. Idiot.

346
00:19:44,516 --> 00:19:46,609
There's no
M protein in my urine.

347
00:19:46,685 --> 00:19:48,312
Odd presentation.

348
00:19:49,254 --> 00:19:52,883
It's so odd that Dr. Cameron
doesn't believe it either.

349
00:19:57,696 --> 00:19:59,095
Just give me 12 more hours.

350
00:19:59,164 --> 00:20:01,598
We had a deal. No more tests.

351
00:20:02,501 --> 00:20:05,732
Fair enough.
Give me six more hours.

352
00:20:07,039 --> 00:20:09,633
Listen, there is no evidence
that you are terminal.

353
00:20:09,741 --> 00:20:11,606
You a man of your word or not?

354
00:20:11,710 --> 00:20:13,405
No, as a matter of fact,
I'm not.

355
00:20:13,478 --> 00:20:16,106
Fine. Then discharge me.

356
00:20:17,883 --> 00:20:20,477
My lungs will slowly
fill with fluid.

357
00:20:21,453 --> 00:20:25,446
I'll gasp to
catch every breath,
but never can.

358
00:20:25,524 --> 00:20:30,689
Every breath will be
petrifying. It'll be slow,
painful, torturous.

359
00:20:34,066 --> 00:20:36,694
You really gonna
let me die like that?

360
00:21:15,307 --> 00:21:17,537
Where are you going?
Nowhere.

361
00:21:35,327 --> 00:21:38,319
Everybody who can walk
should get out of here.

362
00:21:39,398 --> 00:21:40,729
You can't do that.

363
00:21:40,799 --> 00:21:42,096
I can't do what?

364
00:21:42,200 --> 00:21:45,727
Administer a prescription
pain killer to a patient
who's in pain?

365
00:21:45,804 --> 00:21:46,828
Go.

366
00:21:46,905 --> 00:21:49,430
Make sure somebody sees you
downstairs in the cafeteria.

367
00:21:49,508 --> 00:21:51,476
I can't let you do this.

368
00:21:51,910 --> 00:21:55,573
Either I die in pain
or I just die.

369
00:21:55,714 --> 00:21:59,115
That... That's what
the argument is here.
No.

370
00:21:59,184 --> 00:22:01,209
It's about whether you die
or we murder you.

371
00:22:01,286 --> 00:22:05,746
What's gonna happen here
is that someone's getting
a buttload of morphine.

372
00:22:05,824 --> 00:22:08,520
I'm not sure exactly who
at this point.

373
00:22:24,943 --> 00:22:26,968
I can't be a part of this.

374
00:22:51,737 --> 00:22:53,068
Thank you.

375
00:22:56,475 --> 00:23:00,809
I always wondered
exactly what was
on the other side.

376
00:23:02,814 --> 00:23:04,042
Nothing.

377
00:23:18,797 --> 00:23:20,628
(MACHINE BEEPING)

378
00:23:38,383 --> 00:23:40,112
What are you doing?

379
00:23:40,252 --> 00:23:42,152
Getting a laryngoscope.

380
00:23:45,223 --> 00:23:46,747
Don't just stand there, help!

381
00:23:46,825 --> 00:23:48,019
But you told him that...

382
00:23:48,093 --> 00:23:49,924
A little something
I like to call a lie.

383
00:23:49,995 --> 00:23:54,022
It's bad, I know, but it's
way further down the list
than murder.

384
00:24:01,606 --> 00:24:04,769
He's unconscious.
No more whining.

385
00:24:05,744 --> 00:24:07,712
We can keep testing him.

386
00:24:10,148 --> 00:24:13,777
Go get a ventilator.
I'm not gonna do this
all night.

387
00:24:21,460 --> 00:24:23,451
HOUSE: We can legally assume
that he'd consent

388
00:24:23,528 --> 00:24:26,019
to whatever
a reasonable person
would consent to.

389
00:24:26,097 --> 00:24:29,726
And a reasonable person would
obviously consent to being put

390
00:24:29,801 --> 00:24:33,396
in a coma against their will
just to satisfy
your curiosity?

391
00:24:33,638 --> 00:24:37,130
I try to kill him, you're mad.
I don't kill him, you're mad.

392
00:24:37,209 --> 00:24:38,506
All he wanted
was some dignity.

393
00:24:38,577 --> 00:24:40,010
Were you in that room
with him?

394
00:24:40,078 --> 00:24:43,445
Was he wearing a tux
while he choking
on his own plasma?

395
00:24:43,515 --> 00:24:49,215
Keep doing the tests.
Take your time. Do it right.
Go! Get to work.

396
00:24:50,822 --> 00:24:51,982
Wait!

397
00:24:55,927 --> 00:24:59,590
Cameron, why did you
do these cuts so far down
on this MRI of his head?

398
00:24:59,664 --> 00:25:01,222
I wanted get his brain stem
and his C-spine

399
00:25:01,299 --> 00:25:03,233
to make sure
his diaphragm
wasn't paralyzed.

400
00:25:03,301 --> 00:25:06,759
You also caught
the top of his lungs.
There's scarring.

401
00:25:09,508 --> 00:25:12,068
You do know that you
can't really pierce me
with your stares.

402
00:25:12,143 --> 00:25:15,670
Lung scarring along with
the bad bone marrow points
to an autoimmune disease.

403
00:25:15,747 --> 00:25:17,806
Could be pulmonary fibrosis.
Or lupus.

404
00:25:17,883 --> 00:25:19,817
He can kill himself
after we get him better.

405
00:25:19,885 --> 00:25:22,718
Start him on an IVIG
for the lupus
and get a colonoscopy.

406
00:25:22,787 --> 00:25:25,119
The lupus could be
hiding there.

407
00:25:31,796 --> 00:25:33,388
I can't do this.

408
00:25:37,135 --> 00:25:38,534
Drama queen.

409
00:25:39,738 --> 00:25:41,729
Descending colon's clean.

410
00:25:42,807 --> 00:25:44,832
Moving into the sigmoid...

411
00:25:45,911 --> 00:25:48,345
We sure could use
a little more help
around here.

412
00:25:48,413 --> 00:25:50,142
She's doing what
she believes in.

413
00:25:50,215 --> 00:25:53,616
Yeah, if she was acting on
principle, she'd be in here
trying to stop us.

414
00:25:53,718 --> 00:25:55,845
All she's doing is
running away
from the principle,

415
00:25:55,921 --> 00:25:58,116
so she won't have to feel
uncomfortable facing it.

416
00:25:58,189 --> 00:25:59,349
And if you were
acting on principle,

417
00:25:59,424 --> 00:26:02,916
you would have called the cops
when you thought House
was killing the guy.

418
00:26:02,994 --> 00:26:05,155
We better hurry up.
Why?

419
00:26:05,630 --> 00:26:10,033
'Cause I don't think she's
gonna have a problem
deciding what to tell Cuddy.

420
00:26:10,101 --> 00:26:11,432
(MONITOR BEEPING)

421
00:26:11,503 --> 00:26:13,528
FOREMAN: 02 sats,
89 and dropping.

422
00:26:20,812 --> 00:26:22,575
I thought you were only
supposed to put on

423
00:26:22,647 --> 00:26:24,342
a pound a week
during your last trimester.

424
00:26:24,416 --> 00:26:25,940
I'm not pregnant.

425
00:26:26,017 --> 00:26:28,645
I heard about
your little stunt
with Dr. Powell.

426
00:26:28,753 --> 00:26:32,086
Not really a stunt.
More of a trick.
A ruse, a hoodwink.

427
00:26:32,157 --> 00:26:33,624
A lie.
Okay.

428
00:26:34,192 --> 00:26:36,183
Lying is sometimes good,
right?

429
00:26:36,261 --> 00:26:39,822
Like when you're trying to
teach someone a lesson
about humility or something.

430
00:26:39,898 --> 00:26:42,731
All I'm trying to do is
save his life. He's not gonna
learn anything.

431
00:26:42,801 --> 00:26:44,234
I just thought
the same principle
might apply.

432
00:26:44,302 --> 00:26:45,530
It does.

433
00:26:46,338 --> 00:26:47,828
I could have just let him die.

434
00:26:47,906 --> 00:26:50,067
We're not gonna get sued
for keeping him alive.

435
00:26:50,141 --> 00:26:53,076
We could.
I completely disregarded
his wishes.

436
00:26:53,144 --> 00:26:56,443
Do you want me to
disagree with you?
You want me to yell at you?

437
00:26:56,514 --> 00:26:57,538
It is comforting.

438
00:26:57,616 --> 00:27:01,017
We're doctors.
We treat patients,
we don't kill them.

439
00:27:01,987 --> 00:27:03,454
How right you are, Dr. Cuddy!

440
00:27:03,521 --> 00:27:06,684
We also don't pad our bills,
swipe samples
from the pharmacy,

441
00:27:06,758 --> 00:27:09,693
or fantasize about
the teenage daughters
of our patients, either.

442
00:27:09,761 --> 00:27:12,821
True. It better be true,
and you're a pig.

443
00:27:15,300 --> 00:27:17,291
I'm sorry about your leg.

444
00:27:17,435 --> 00:27:21,064
Yeah. We really should
spend some time
talking about that.

445
00:27:21,306 --> 00:27:22,933
The IVIG made him worse.

446
00:27:23,008 --> 00:27:24,805
02 sats plummeted.

447
00:27:25,410 --> 00:27:27,435
So we know it's not lupus.

448
00:27:27,812 --> 00:27:28,836
What else could it be?

449
00:27:28,913 --> 00:27:31,245
Idiopathic
pulmonary fibrosis.

450
00:27:31,316 --> 00:27:34,410
We're gonna need
an open lung biopsy
to confirm.

451
00:27:35,253 --> 00:27:37,483
So now we're gonna
operate on the guy?

452
00:27:37,555 --> 00:27:41,719
Well, unless you've invented
a new way of doing
an open lung biopsy.

453
00:27:44,663 --> 00:27:46,927
When you searched
Dr. Powell's office,

454
00:27:46,998 --> 00:27:51,059
did you find a copy of
the January 1967
<i>Massachusetts Medical Journal?</i>

455
00:27:51,136 --> 00:27:52,160
Why?

456
00:27:52,237 --> 00:27:54,262
I just figured
if you're not doing any work,

457
00:27:54,339 --> 00:27:56,569
you might like something
to pass the time.

458
00:27:56,641 --> 00:27:58,666
The centerfold's a killer.

459
00:28:13,058 --> 00:28:14,184
How's your leg?

460
00:28:14,259 --> 00:28:16,659
It hurts. And it's gonna
keep on hurting.

461
00:28:16,761 --> 00:28:17,921
You gonna keep on asking?

462
00:28:17,996 --> 00:28:19,759
How's Ezra Powell?

463
00:28:21,099 --> 00:28:22,498
Resting comfortably.

464
00:28:22,600 --> 00:28:24,830
That's not what Cameron says.

465
00:28:24,903 --> 00:28:26,996
I hate practicing medicine
in high school.

466
00:28:27,072 --> 00:28:30,701
He's not asking you to
help him kill himself.
He's just asking for help.

467
00:28:30,775 --> 00:28:32,242
The disease will kill him.

468
00:28:32,310 --> 00:28:34,676
I know what he was asking for.
I just said, "No."

469
00:28:34,746 --> 00:28:37,180
You've done it before,
plenty of times.

470
00:28:37,248 --> 00:28:38,806
To patients that I knew
were terminal.

471
00:28:38,883 --> 00:28:40,111
Oh, give me a break.

472
00:28:40,185 --> 00:28:42,449
This has nothing to do
with saving a life.

473
00:28:42,520 --> 00:28:44,044
You just can't bear
the thought of a patient dying

474
00:28:44,122 --> 00:28:46,113
before you've been able to
figure out why.

475
00:28:46,191 --> 00:28:49,354
If we're gonna keep refusing
to cure patients
just to rein in my ego,

476
00:28:49,427 --> 00:28:51,918
then we might start having
a little problem
in patient recruitment.

477
00:28:51,996 --> 00:28:55,295
Worried about meeting
your one-patient-a-week quota?

478
00:28:55,500 --> 00:28:59,368
I'm a cripple, remember?
Accommodations must be made.

479
00:29:08,880 --> 00:29:12,338
Wedge of left lobe isolated,
and removed.

480
00:29:14,552 --> 00:29:15,712
Clamp.

481
00:29:19,424 --> 00:29:21,153
Why'd you have me
look up that article?

482
00:29:21,226 --> 00:29:22,488
Did you find it interesting?

483
00:29:22,560 --> 00:29:24,960
He injected newborn babies
with radioactive agents

484
00:29:25,029 --> 00:29:26,690
just to see
if they had urethral reflux.

485
00:29:26,765 --> 00:29:27,857
He was curious.

486
00:29:27,932 --> 00:29:30,400
He didn't even
tell their parents
he was doing an experiment.

487
00:29:30,468 --> 00:29:32,402
He wasn't doing anything
his peers weren't doing.

488
00:29:32,504 --> 00:29:34,665
His peers at Tuskegee
and Willowbrook?

489
00:29:34,739 --> 00:29:37,333
He ignored the rights of a few
to save many.

490
00:29:37,408 --> 00:29:39,239
So you're okay
with what he did?

491
00:29:39,310 --> 00:29:41,301
It doesn't matter
what I think.

492
00:29:41,379 --> 00:29:43,472
It's what you think
that's relevant.

493
00:29:43,982 --> 00:29:47,975
Because if I think
less of him,
I'll help you more?

494
00:29:50,321 --> 00:29:51,788
You're wrong.

495
00:29:52,490 --> 00:29:55,118
The fact that a patient
did bad things
doesn't change anything.

496
00:29:55,193 --> 00:29:58,026
He still deserves to
have some control
over his own body.

497
00:29:58,096 --> 00:30:00,564
If he had any control
over his own body,
he'd be dead.

498
00:30:00,632 --> 00:30:03,999
Some control. We can withhold
treatment without killing him.

499
00:30:04,068 --> 00:30:06,195
No, you can't!

500
00:30:06,271 --> 00:30:10,765
You either help him live
or you help him die.
You can't have it both ways.

501
00:30:15,346 --> 00:30:17,541
Well, I guess it's not IPF.

502
00:30:18,082 --> 00:30:20,050
(MACHINE BEEPING)

503
00:30:20,118 --> 00:30:23,679
Maybe he'll die right now,
make everything easy
for all of us.

504
00:30:28,393 --> 00:30:30,953
Heart rate's fast. BP's low.

505
00:30:33,331 --> 00:30:36,266
No breath sounds on
the right side.
He's dropped his right lung.

506
00:30:36,334 --> 00:30:39,770
Air's building up
in his chest,
compressing his heart.

507
00:30:51,950 --> 00:30:53,144
Heart rate's decreasing.

508
00:30:53,218 --> 00:30:54,947
BP's stabilizing.

509
00:31:15,240 --> 00:31:16,969
What are you doing?

510
00:31:23,414 --> 00:31:26,542
He withdraws from pain stimuli
on the left side
but not the right.

511
00:31:26,618 --> 00:31:28,245
Those are just reflex arcs.

512
00:31:28,319 --> 00:31:29,513
He's under anesthesia.

513
00:31:29,587 --> 00:31:32,147
Or he's lost sensation
in some places.

514
00:31:32,223 --> 00:31:35,192
Or the hypoxia from the arrest
stunned his CNS.

515
00:31:35,260 --> 00:31:37,728
Only one way to tell.
Do somatosensory
evoked potentials.

516
00:31:37,795 --> 00:31:40,423
We can't do that
while he's in a coma.

517
00:31:40,765 --> 00:31:43,893
Only two ways to tell.
Get a hammer and check
his deep tendon reflexes.

518
00:31:43,968 --> 00:31:47,267
It won't work.
He needs muscle relaxants
to be on the ventilator.

519
00:31:47,405 --> 00:31:50,033
Only one more way to tell.
Pupillary reflexes.

520
00:31:50,108 --> 00:31:52,474
All that tests is
the brain stem.
See, I was right.

521
00:31:52,543 --> 00:31:55,273
Only one way to tell.
Do somatosensory
evoked potentials.

522
00:31:55,346 --> 00:31:57,405
I just said,
we can't do that
while he's in a coma.

523
00:31:57,482 --> 00:31:59,006
So wake him up.

524
00:32:13,398 --> 00:32:16,128
Don't go towards the light.

525
00:32:17,635 --> 00:32:19,933
You'll fall
and break your hip.

526
00:32:23,408 --> 00:32:25,171
(COUGHING)

527
00:32:44,429 --> 00:32:47,159
What's happening? I...

528
00:32:49,233 --> 00:32:51,098
You took a little nap.

529
00:32:52,704 --> 00:32:55,901
I thought I told you
I didn't want...

530
00:32:55,974 --> 00:32:58,135
Sorry. A little deaf
in one ear.

531
00:32:58,609 --> 00:33:00,634
Your bone marrow
is hypocellular.

532
00:33:00,712 --> 00:33:03,909
We've ruled out lupus
and pulmonary fibrosis.

533
00:33:04,048 --> 00:33:07,176
But it looks like it could be
attacking your nerves.

534
00:33:07,251 --> 00:33:11,153
So this is all a waste?
A huge failure?

535
00:33:12,790 --> 00:33:16,419
Lmpossible.
You're Gregory House.

536
00:33:16,561 --> 00:33:18,961
We need to attach some sensors
to your skin.

537
00:33:19,030 --> 00:33:20,019
No.

538
00:33:20,098 --> 00:33:21,793
Look, we can't
do what you want.

539
00:33:21,899 --> 00:33:24,697
We've assigned a nurse
to watch you,
so you can't do it either.

540
00:33:24,836 --> 00:33:26,463
So you might as well
just let us do the test.

541
00:33:26,537 --> 00:33:28,368
No. I want to be discharged.

542
00:33:28,473 --> 00:33:31,169
You can't be discharged.
You've got two chest tubes in.

543
00:33:31,242 --> 00:33:32,573
Then take them out!

544
00:33:32,643 --> 00:33:34,372
Oh, get over yourself.

545
00:33:34,479 --> 00:33:37,346
The ventilator puffed up
your lungs. You'll be fine
for a few hours.

546
00:33:37,415 --> 00:33:39,440
Just let us run the tests.

547
00:33:42,120 --> 00:33:43,212
Okay.

548
00:33:44,789 --> 00:33:47,485
But first,
let's clean you up a little.

549
00:33:50,361 --> 00:33:52,295
What...
Does that feel nice?

550
00:33:52,363 --> 00:33:54,422
What are you trying to prove?
Just cleaning him up.

551
00:33:54,499 --> 00:33:56,399
What does it look like?

552
00:33:57,301 --> 00:34:00,361
Pay no attention
to the man behind the curtain.

553
00:34:03,574 --> 00:34:04,802
Get out!

554
00:34:05,410 --> 00:34:09,107
Okay, I'm going already.
Can't you see I'm a cripple?

555
00:34:11,783 --> 00:34:13,478
Okay, so you've
got me curious.

556
00:34:13,551 --> 00:34:14,609
I was right.

557
00:34:14,685 --> 00:34:17,176
Whatever is
attacking his lungs
is attacking his nerves.

558
00:34:17,255 --> 00:34:18,984
And you got that by
splashing ice water on him?

559
00:34:19,057 --> 00:34:21,753
No sensation in the left leg,
abdomen, right arm.

560
00:34:21,826 --> 00:34:23,191
Technology's overrated.

561
00:34:23,261 --> 00:34:25,024
That means the clean MRI
of his brain means

562
00:34:25,096 --> 00:34:26,563
it's just affecting
the peripheral nerves.

563
00:34:26,664 --> 00:34:27,722
And bone marrow.

564
00:34:27,799 --> 00:34:29,426
Kawasaki's would explain
the kidney failure.

565
00:34:29,500 --> 00:34:31,593
So would lymphoma.
So would sarcoidosis.

566
00:34:31,669 --> 00:34:34,763
All potentially treatable.
The question is which?

567
00:34:34,839 --> 00:34:37,774
We need to catch
the little bastards
in the act.

568
00:34:37,842 --> 00:34:39,036
What's the largest organ?

569
00:34:39,110 --> 00:34:41,340
Skin.
We need to get a piece.

570
00:34:42,146 --> 00:34:45,115
Sure. We'll just wait until
he leaves his room
without his skin,

571
00:34:45,183 --> 00:34:47,208
sneak in and take a piece.

572
00:34:48,186 --> 00:34:51,178
I want you to get
a skin sample for a biopsy.

573
00:34:51,389 --> 00:34:53,380
And I want to get
a foot massage
from Johnny Damon.

574
00:34:53,458 --> 00:34:57,451
Kawasaki's disease, lymphoma,
and sarcoidosis
are all treatable.

575
00:34:57,562 --> 00:35:00,998
And it could be a hundred
other things that aren't
treatable. You have no idea.

576
00:35:01,065 --> 00:35:02,464
But you do.

577
00:35:02,767 --> 00:35:04,598
You know everything.
I didn't say that I...

578
00:35:04,669 --> 00:35:06,000
Exactly!

579
00:35:06,504 --> 00:35:09,405
You can't decide
if we're helping
or hurting him.

580
00:35:09,474 --> 00:35:13,934
If it's good or bad,
or if you want paper, plastic,
or a burlap sack.

581
00:35:15,746 --> 00:35:17,373
Do your damn job.

582
00:35:19,717 --> 00:35:21,708
I'm not gonna lie to him.

583
00:35:25,857 --> 00:35:29,816
Fine. Tell the truth.
Just get me a pound of flesh.

584
00:35:37,902 --> 00:35:38,994
What do you want?

585
00:35:39,070 --> 00:35:42,267
House wants to
biopsy your skin.
He sent me to get it.

586
00:35:42,340 --> 00:35:43,398
And you agreed?

587
00:35:43,474 --> 00:35:47,205
I had nothing to do with
putting you in a coma or
any of the subsequent tests.

588
00:35:47,278 --> 00:35:49,041
Which brings us to now.

589
00:35:49,113 --> 00:35:50,740
I read some of your articles.

590
00:35:51,315 --> 00:35:53,306
There were a lot of them.

591
00:35:55,253 --> 00:35:58,120
1967 <i>Massachusetts</i>
<i>Medical Journal.</i>

592
00:35:59,090 --> 00:36:03,288
You radiated babies,
just like that. No forms,
no questions, nothing.

593
00:36:03,361 --> 00:36:05,921
Who knows how many cancers
you caused?

594
00:36:05,997 --> 00:36:07,464
I don't know.

595
00:36:08,099 --> 00:36:10,397
But what I do know is,
we discovered techniques that

596
00:36:10,468 --> 00:36:14,996
prevent fatal kidney failures
in hundreds of thousands
of other kids.

597
00:36:15,406 --> 00:36:16,532
You're not sorry.

598
00:36:16,607 --> 00:36:18,575
I don't regret what I did.

599
00:36:18,643 --> 00:36:23,512
Informed consent,
patient rights...
Holds back research.

600
00:36:26,584 --> 00:36:28,381
(GROANS)

601
00:36:28,853 --> 00:36:30,411
What the hell are you doing?

602
00:36:30,488 --> 00:36:33,548
Informed consent
is holding back our diagnosis.

603
00:36:34,392 --> 00:36:35,859
Good for you.

604
00:36:37,495 --> 00:36:42,194
Finally standing up
for something.
Acting on what you believe.

605
00:36:47,972 --> 00:36:50,941
Dr. House? Hi. How are you?

606
00:36:51,209 --> 00:36:53,177
Not as good as you think I am.

607
00:36:53,244 --> 00:36:55,576
Don't worry, I'm not
stalking you. My dad
just lost his medicine.

608
00:36:55,646 --> 00:36:57,409
I needed to come back
for another prescription.

609
00:36:57,481 --> 00:36:58,880
Yeah, right.

610
00:36:59,183 --> 00:37:00,741
He's moving it
on the street, isn't he?

611
00:37:00,818 --> 00:37:03,616
Yeah, my dad,
the meth kingpin.

612
00:37:05,890 --> 00:37:08,688
Why haven't you returned
any of my calls?

613
00:37:10,127 --> 00:37:13,062
I plan to
in a couple of years.

614
00:37:13,431 --> 00:37:17,026
I was just calling to say
thank you and to tell you
how impressed I was.

615
00:37:17,101 --> 00:37:19,831
You diagnosed my dad
by just looking at him.

616
00:37:19,904 --> 00:37:21,804
I felt his glands, too.

617
00:37:24,075 --> 00:37:26,669
Well, there's my dad.
I've got to go.

618
00:37:27,211 --> 00:37:28,337
Yeah, me, too.

619
00:37:28,412 --> 00:37:32,280
And, you really don't have to
wait a couple of years
to return my calls.

620
00:37:32,516 --> 00:37:35,041
Just six months,
till I turn 18.

621
00:37:46,697 --> 00:37:49,291
It's not Kawasaki's either.
What next?

622
00:37:49,367 --> 00:37:50,595
Congo red.

623
00:37:50,901 --> 00:37:51,959
Amyloidosis?

624
00:37:52,036 --> 00:37:54,231
What the hell else
would I mean by Congo red?

625
00:37:54,305 --> 00:37:55,294
It's not on the list.

626
00:37:55,373 --> 00:37:56,738
There's no reason
for it to be on the list.

627
00:37:56,807 --> 00:38:00,038
An abnormal protein
is building up
inside the cells of his body,

628
00:38:00,111 --> 00:38:01,874
shutting down his organs
one by one.
It explains everything.

629
00:38:01,946 --> 00:38:05,109
The infiltrates on the x-ray,
the bone marrow,
kidney failure.

630
00:38:05,182 --> 00:38:08,640
We rejected amyloidosis
because it didn't fit
the first symptom we found.

631
00:38:08,719 --> 00:38:10,050
It would affect his heart.
It did.

632
00:38:10,121 --> 00:38:11,281
It wasn't on the stress test.

633
00:38:11,389 --> 00:38:13,152
We didn't push him
hard enough.

634
00:38:13,224 --> 00:38:15,624
Add the stain
and let's find out.

635
00:38:17,194 --> 00:38:18,786
Congo red added.

636
00:38:19,530 --> 00:38:22,522
Change the polarization
of the light already.

637
00:38:30,174 --> 00:38:32,608
That means
it should be treatable.

638
00:38:32,943 --> 00:38:34,433
How the hell did you
pull that out of...

639
00:38:34,512 --> 00:38:36,742
Not out of mine.
I had a muse.

640
00:38:39,183 --> 00:38:43,950
Oh, God. Protein type AA.

641
00:39:01,939 --> 00:39:03,065
Dr. House...

642
00:39:03,140 --> 00:39:04,573
You have amyloidosis.

643
00:39:05,676 --> 00:39:08,941
It's in your lungs, kidneys,
bone marrow and brain.

644
00:39:10,915 --> 00:39:13,110
Why should I believe you now?

645
00:39:17,688 --> 00:39:21,488
If I was lying,
I wouldn't tell you
the sub-type is AA.

646
00:39:23,427 --> 00:39:24,894
It's terminal.

647
00:39:27,231 --> 00:39:28,994
Congratulations.

648
00:39:31,469 --> 00:39:33,232
You got your answer.

649
00:39:35,106 --> 00:39:37,700
<i>(INTO DUST</i> PLAYING)

650
00:41:07,097 --> 00:41:09,258
Ezra Powell
passed away last night.

651
00:41:09,333 --> 00:41:11,528
I'm sure you already
knew about that.

652
00:41:11,936 --> 00:41:13,801
No, I just got in.

653
00:41:14,104 --> 00:41:18,063
The nurse charted at 2:00 a.m.
He was stable,
breathing labored but regular.

654
00:41:18,142 --> 00:41:21,669
Then, at 2:30, he suddenly
stopped. You know
anything about that?

655
00:41:21,745 --> 00:41:24,680
If I did, would you
really want to know?

656
00:42:38,656 --> 00:42:40,283
I'm proud of you.